    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1948-05-24T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1948-05-24T12:00:00-05:00" n="178"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d178">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 Council/5–2448: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_CJ1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Caffery</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1948-05-24T18:00:00+01:00"
                            >May 24, 1948—6 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2755. In further explanation of why <persName corresp="#p_BG1">Bidault</persName>
                    gave me the two notes (<gloss target="#t_mytel1">mytel</gloss> 2720 and 2724 May
                        21<note n="1" xml:id="d178fn1">Neither the notes nor the telegrams under
                        reference here are printed, but see telegram 2214, May 21, from London, <ref
                            target="#pg_266">p. 266</ref>, and footnotes 2 and 3 thereto.</note>),
                        <persName corresp="#p_CJ2">Chauvel</persName> gave me to understand that
                        <persName corresp="#p_BG1">Bidault</persName> is in a panic over the
                    attitude of the non-Communist French press during the past two weeks in regard
                    to the London conversations and is especially concerned over the attitude of the
                    Socialists whom he expected to be friendly to his position. (He was not
                    referring to very recent articles obviously inspired by the Quai d’Orsay. I have
                        <pb facs="0308" n="274" xml:id="pg_274"/> referred to these articles and let
                    the French Government know in plain terms what I think of them.)</p>
                <p>In other words <persName corresp="#p_BG1">Bidault</persName> now fears that he
                    has gone too far to meet us at London and is trying to find a way to crawl
                    out.</p>
                <p>Sent Department 2755; repeated London 426 and Berlin 241.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_CJ1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Caffery</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
